{{Confuse|Trophic level}} The '''trophic level index''' (TLI) is used in [[New Zealand]] as a measure of nutrient status of lakes.<ref>[http://www.mfe.govt.nz/environmental-reporting/freshwater/lake/trophic-level.html New Zealand Ministry for the Environment] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100522140630/http://www.mfe.govt.nz/environmental-reporting/freshwater/lake/trophic-level.html |date=2010-05-22 }} - Trophic Level Index for lakes</ref> It is similar to the [[trophic state index]] but was proposed as alternative that suited New Zealand.<ref>{{cite book|last=Burns|first=Noel|author2=Graham Bryers |author3=Eddie Bowman |title=Protocol for Monitoring Trophic Levels of New Zealand Lakes and Reservoirs|date=March 2000|url=http://www.mfe.govt.nz/publications/fresh-water-environmental-reporting/protocol-monitoring-trophic-levels-new-zealand|accessdate=2017-05-09}}</ref>
The system uses four criteria, phosphorus and nitrogen concentrations, as well as visual clarity and algal biomass weighted equally.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Burns | first1 = Noel | last2 = McIntosh | first2 = John | last3 = Scholes| first3 = Paul | title = Strategies for Managing the Lakes of the Rotorua District, New Zealand | journal = Lake and Reservoir Management | volume = 21 | issue = 1 | pages = 61–72 | date = 2005 | url = http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/pdf/10.1080/07438140509354413 | doi = 10.1080/07438140509354413 }}</ref>
